Visual Analytics Group Project

Introduction to our dataset

Dataset is about prices of used cars along with features like mpg, engine size, etc. Dataset contains numerical and categorical features in order to be easy for visualization. This is dataset is about 100,000 listings, which have been separated into files corresponding to each car manufacturer.

In the Plot1, Hist plot shows how many cars you could find in the data with certian price. So around 20k price, you will see the majority of cars with this price.
In the Plot2, The Scatter plot between the mileage and the price shows that the majority of cars in the previous graph are with high mileage. This makes sense, since most of used cars have a low price if the mileage is high.
In the Plot3, Just the mean of prices over years starting from 1995.
In the Plot4, with each transmission we count the number of cars that using certain type of Fuel. If you are seeking fo a manual-transmission car, you will most likly find it a Petrol one.

  • People who want to buy a new car have to pay higher tax compared to older cars.
  • Engine size and year highly affects the price of a car.
  • Higher mileage means lower price.
  • Correlation between mileage and year is highly negatively correlated.

In [19]:
@interact(year=(1970, 2020))
def plot_fuel_type(year):
    petrol_cars[petrol_cars.index>=year].plot(kind = 'line', label = 'Petrol', figsize = (12, 8))
    diesel_cars[diesel_cars.index>=year].plot(kind = 'line', label = 'Diesel', figsize = (12, 8))
    hybrid_cars[hybrid_cars.index>=year].plot(kind = 'line', label = 'Hybrid', figsize = (12, 8))

    plt.title('Petrol vs. Diesel vs. Hybrid', fontsize = 16)
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize = 16)
    plt.ylabel('Average price', fontsize = 16)
    plt.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1,1), ncol=1)

interactive(children=(IntSlider(value=1995, description='year', max=2020, min=1970), Output()), _dom_classes=(

It's interesting to see that from 1970-2000 diesel cars have sold on average for far higher prices than petrol. Hybrid cars have only started being in the market in the early 2000s. Nowadays the fueltype doesn't affect the price much. We made the graph interactive to easily compare price trends in diffrent periods of interest and to minimize effect of outliers.

Dimensionality Reduction

for refrence:

Finally, cluster similar items and show the clustering result. Since you have high-dimensional data, use an appropriate dimension reduction technique (t-SNE, PCA, etc.) to reduce the number of dimensions for 2D plotting. Implement the following steps:

  • Let the user interactively select the cluster algorithms and/or its parameters.
  • Select one/more cluster/s from the resulting visualization.
  • Use the selected data with its cluster affiliation in a second interactive visualization. The goal is to create a simple overview+detail visualization setup.
  • Interpret the result.
In [30]:
df_dim_red = df.sample(5000).copy() # Altair accepts max 5000 elements
df_dim_red.drop(['model'], axis=1, inplace=True)  

label_enc_manf = LabelEncoder()
label_enc_trans = LabelEncoder()
label_enc_fuel = LabelEncoder()

#df_dim_red = df_dim_red[df_dim_red.manufacturer.isin(['toyota', 'merc'])]
df_dim_red["manufacturer"] = label_enc_manf.fit_transform(df_dim_red["manufacturer"])
df_dim_red["transmission"] = label_enc_trans.fit_transform(df_dim_red["transmission"])
df_dim_red["fuelType"] = label_enc_fuel.fit_transform(df_dim_red["fuelType"])

n_clusters = len(label_enc_manf.classes_)  # same as number of manufacturers

PCA dimensionality reduction with k-means clustering

In [31]:
preprocessor_pca = Pipeline(
    [
        ("scaler", MinMaxScaler()),
        ("pca", PCA(n_components=2, random_state=42)),
        ]
    )

clusterer = Pipeline(
    [
        (
            "kmeans",
            KMeans(
                n_clusters=n_clusters,
                init="random",
                n_init=50,
                max_iter=500,
                random_state=42,
                ),
            ),
        ]
    )

pipe_pca = Pipeline(
    [
        ("preprocessor_pca", preprocessor_pca),
        ("clusterer", clusterer)
        ]
    )

pcadf = pd.DataFrame()
In [32]:
@interact(year=(1970, 2020), price=True, transmission=True, mileage=True, fuelType=True, mpg=True, engineSize=True)
def visualize_clusterring(year, price, transmission, mpg, mileage, fuelType, engineSize):    
    cols = []
    for attr, attr_name in zip([year, price, transmission, mpg, mileage, fuelType, mpg, engineSize],
                              ['year', 'price', 'transmission', 'mileage', 'fuelType', 'mpg', 'engineSize']):
        if attr: 
            cols.append(attr_name)
    
    x = df_dim_red[df_dim_red.year >= year].loc[:, cols].values
    
    pipe_pca.fit(x)
    preprocessed_data = pipe_pca["preprocessor_pca"].transform(x)
    predicted_labels = pipe_pca["clusterer"]["kmeans"].labels_
    
    global pcadf
    pcadf = pd.DataFrame(
        preprocessed_data,
        columns=["component_1", "component_2"],
        )
    
    pcadf["predicted_cluster"] = predicted_labels  # output from k-means
    
    pcadf["true_label"] = label_enc_manf.inverse_transform(df_dim_red["manufacturer"])
    
    plot_clusters = alt.Chart(pcadf).mark_point().encode(
        alt.X('component_1'),
        alt.Y('component_2'),
        color=f'predicted_cluster:N',
        tooltip=['true_label']
    ).configure_title(
    fontSize=17,
    font='Courier',
    anchor='start',
    color='gray'
    ).properties(
        title=f"Clustering PCA dimensionality reduction, followed by k-means (k={n_clusters})",
        width=1000,
        height=600
    ).interactive()
    
    return plot_clusters

interactive(children=(IntSlider(value=1995, description='year', max=2020, min=1970), Checkbox(value=True, desc

@interact(cluster_num=(1, 8))

def visualize_cluseter(cluster_num):
    cluster_ = pcadf[pcadf.predicted_cluster==cluster_num-1]
    
    if len(cluster_) > 5000:
        cluster_ = cluster_.sample(5000)
        
    # plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    # sns.scatterplot(data=cluster_, x='component_1', y='component_2', hue='true_label')
    print(len(cluster_))
    
    plot_clusters = alt.Chart(cluster_).mark_point().encode(
        alt.X('component_1'),
        alt.Y('component_2'),
        color=f'true_label:N',
    ).configure_title(
    fontSize=17,
    font='Courier',
    anchor='start',
    color='gray'
    ).properties(
        title=f"Visualizing cluster {cluster_num}",

        height=600

We tried to use dimensionality reduction to reduce a selected number of features to two components to capture the variance in the data, and then follow that with a k-means clustering algorithm to try and label points in the reduced space as one of the manufacturers (e.g. audi, bmw, etc.) The k in the k-means is chosen as the number of labels (i.e. manufacturers.) We tried various selections of features , hyperparameters, as well as considering only some manufacturers (e.g. only bmw and toyota.) Unfortunately, we were not able to find a clear-cut separation between datapoints in the reduced dimension space. We think that this is due to the inherent difficult in the nature of the data to reduce it into two components. The plot distinguishes clusters based on color; the true label of the data is distinguished via the different marker types.

PCA

In [34]:
df_ = df[df.manufacturer == 'bmw'].copy().reset_index()
cols = ['year', 'price', 'mpg', 'tax']#, 'tax', 'mpg', 'engineSize']

color_dict = {
    0: 'red',
    1: 'blue',
    2: '#bebada',
    3: 'yellow',
    4: 'black'
}

def visualize_pca(df:pd.DataFrame, cols=[], y='', n_components:int = 2):
    x = df.loc[:, cols].values
    x = StandardScaler().fit_transform(x)
    
    pca = PCA(n_components=n_components)
    principalComponents = pca.fit_transform(x)
    
    principalDf = pd.DataFrame(data = principalComponents, columns = ['component_'+str(i+1) for i in range(n_components)])
    finalDf = pd.concat([principalDf, df_[[y]]], axis = 1)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))
    if n_components==3:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1, projection='3d') 
    else:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1', fontsize = 15)
    ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2', fontsize = 15)
    if n_components==3:
        ax.set_zlabel('Principal Component 3', fontsize = 15)
    ax.set_title('PCA', fontsize = 20)
    targets = df[y].unique()
    colors = list(color_dict.values())[: len(targets)]
    for target, color in zip(targets,colors):
        indicesToKeep = finalDf[y] == target
        if n_components==3:
            ax.scatter(finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_1'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_2'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_3'],
                       c = color, s = 50)
        else:
            ax.scatter(finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_1'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_2'],
                       c = color, s = 50)
    ax.legend(targets)
    ax.grid()
    return pca

def visualize_tsne(df:pd.DataFrame, cols=[], y='', n_components:int = 2, perplexity:float=30, learning_rate: float=200,
                  n_iter: int=1000):
    x = df.loc[:, cols].values
    x = StandardScaler().fit_transform(x)
    
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=n_components, verbose=0, perplexity=perplexity, n_iter=n_iter, learning_rate=learning_rate)
    tsne_results = tsne.fit_transform(x)
    
    principalDf = pd.DataFrame(data = tsne_results, columns = ['component_'+str(i+1) for i in range(n_components)])
    finalDf = pd.concat([principalDf, df_[[y]]], axis = 1)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))
    if n_components==3:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1, projection='3d') 
    else:
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1', fontsize = 15)
    ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2', fontsize = 15)
    if n_components==3:
        ax.set_zlabel('Principal Component 3', fontsize = 15)
    ax.set_title('TSNE', fontsize = 20)
    targets = df[y].unique()
    colors = list(color_dict.values())[: len(targets)]
    for target, color in zip(targets,colors):
        indicesToKeep = finalDf[y] == target
        if n_components==3:
            ax.scatter(finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_1'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_2'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_3'],
                       c = color, s = 50)
        else:
            ax.scatter(finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_1'],
                       finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'component_2'],
                       c = color, s = 50)
    ax.legend(targets)
    ax.grid()
